```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\textbf{Binary tree}

\textbf{Combinatorics}

\bigskip

$C_{n}$

\begin{tikzpicture}[level distance=1.5cm, sibling distance=2cm]
  \node {C}
    child {node[label={$i=0$}] {C}}
    child {node[label={$n-1$}] {C}
          child[missing] {}
          child {node[label={$n-1-i$}] {C}}};
\end{tikzpicture}

\bigskip

=

\bigskip

\displaystyle \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} C_i C_{n-1-i}

\bigskip

For any positive integer $n$, it follows that

$C_{n}$

\begin{tikzpicture}[level distance=1.5cm, sibling distance=2cm]
  \node {C}
    child[missing] {}
    child {node[label={$n-1$}] {C};};
\end{tikzpicture}

\bigskip

is the Catalan number of index $n$.

The above parenthesized strings should not be confused with the set of words of length $2n$ in the Dyck language, which consist only of parentheses in such a way that they are properly balanced. The number of such strings satisfies the same recursive description (each Dyck word of length $2n$ is determined by the Dyck subword enclosed by the initial '(' and its matching ')' together with the Dyck subword remaining after that closing parenthesis, whose lengths $2i$ and $2j$ satisfy $i+j+1=n$); this number is therefore also the Catalan number $C_{n}$. So there are also five Dyck words of length 6:

\begin{itemize}
\item ()()()
\item ()(())
\item (())()
\item (()())
\item ((()))
\end{itemize}

These Dyck words do not correspond to binary trees in the same way. Instead, they are related by the following recursively defined bijection: the Dyck word equal to the empty string corresponds to the binary tree of size 0 with only one leaf. Any other Dyck word can be written as $(w_1) (w_2)$, where $w_1$ is a Dyck word and $w_2$ is obtained from $w_1$ by removing the first symbol and adding a new symbol at the beginning.
\end{document}
```

