\begin{document}

\textbf{Binary tree representation of Dyck words:}

The binary trees corresponding to the Dyck words $w\_1$ and $w\_2$, which are themselves (possibly empty), are defined as follows: the two written parentheses must be matched. The bijection is then defined by letting the words $w\_1$ and $w\_2$ correspond to the binary trees that are the left and right children of the root.

\textbf{An alternative bijective correspondence:}

Enclose the Dyck word in an extra pair of parentheses, so that the result can be interpreted as a Lisp list expression (with the empty list () as only occurring atom); then the dotted-pair expression for that proper list is a fully parenthesized expression (with NIL as symbol and '.' as operator) describing the corresponding binary tree (which is, in fact, the internal representation of the proper list).

For example, the Dyck word $w\_1$ corresponds to the binary tree:

\begin{equation*}
\DyckWord{1} = (\,(\,) \,(\,) \,)
\end{equation*}

And the Dyck word $w\_2$ corresponds to the binary tree:

\begin{equation*}
\DyckWord{2} = (\,(\,) \,(\,) \,)
\end{equation*}

The ability to represent binary trees as strings of symbols and parentheses implies that binary trees can represent the elements of a free magma on a singleton set.

\end{document}
